sm, pervasive antisemitism and racism, and widespread isolationism. Collecting newspaper and magazine articles, popular culture materials, and government records, Americans and the Holocaust is a valuable resource for students and historians seeking to shed light on this dark era in world history. To explore further, visit the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum's digital exhibit, available here: https://exhibitions.ushmm.org/americans-and-the-holocaust Published in association with the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xForeign public opinion, American. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xInfluence. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aNational socialism in popular culturezUnited States. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPress coveragezUnited States. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPublic opinion. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAmerica, United States, Holocaust, Germany, 1930s, 1940s, Nazis, power, Jews, Jewish, Americans, war, wars, refugees, refugee, refugee resettlement, military, military intervention, political cartoons, ads, advertisments, film, newspapers, magazines, periodicals, classrooms, libraries, museums, German Nazism, 1920s, government.1 aBloomfield, Sara J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreene, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPhillips, Edward, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197882172940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978821729423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978821729/original  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13